  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Traceability between the lifecycle artifacts is important for governance and impact analysis, it facilitates the&#xD;
    overall quality of the software or systems application being developed, and enables teams to make informed changes,&#xD;
    reduce risk, and improve agility.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    By creating relationships between software artifacts across all disciplines, including design management, requirements&#xD;
    management, change and configuration management, and quality management, and establishing lifecycle traceability, you&#xD;
    can improve quality in the following ways:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Share and combine information about projects so that project teams and stakeholders are better able to understand&#xD;
        the application being developed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Assess and manage the impact of change on elements in the design by performing impact analysis.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Identify and close traceability gaps to ensure full coverage across requirements, design, development, and test.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Ensure that the design satisfies the business requirements.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        View related artifacts and make informed decisions about the project.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
